[
    {
        "content": "<p>In Schmid et al. (<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2009.03297\">2020</a>) the authors define measurement of a deterministic variable, that is a variable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> in a Kleisli category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span></span></span></span></span> as in Fritz et al. (<a href=\"http://arxiv.org/pdf/2010.07416v1\">2020</a>), in an experiment as operation on string diagrams like this (adapted from diagram (86) on page 15 in Schmid et al. (2020)):<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/LmNwOma9xiOGgs-UXydBZBBc/StringMeas.png\">StringMeas.png</a> </p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/LmNwOma9xiOGgs-UXydBZBBc/StringMeas.png\" title=\"StringMeas.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/LmNwOma9xiOGgs-UXydBZBBc/StringMeas.png\"></a></div><p>This operation follows rules with respect to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">l</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{del}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">l</span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{copy}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.63888em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">p</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">y</span></span></span></span></span>: (1) measurements do not affect the variables in the diagram (equation (88)), and (2) multiple measurements of the same variable are equivalent to multiple copies of one of these measurements (equation (89)). </p>\n<p>I would like to use a nondeterministic version of this measurement in order to model sampling from populations. In a Kleisli category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span></span></span></span></span> with monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> consider a population to be a distribution over a variable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span>, that is an element of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PZ.</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span> Inpired by <a href=\"#narrow/stream/238032-Categorical-Probability.20and.20Statistics.202020.20workshop/topic/Categorical.20Radon-Nikodym/near/205870566\">comments</a> by <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276071\">@Nathaniel Virgo</span>, let's draw variables in the first power of the monad like this<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/b6Wa7XFImDw3mqafEgWR30x9/StringTube.png\">StringTube.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/b6Wa7XFImDw3mqafEgWR30x9/StringTube.png\" title=\"StringTube.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/b6Wa7XFImDw3mqafEgWR30x9/StringTube.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 222962229,
        "sender_full_name": "Christoph Thies",
        "timestamp": 1610775797
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As above, we have the operation of measuring the deterministic observable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PZ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span>:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/q4pPyA1PYTgCyrj5_CTYDNlS/StringTubeMeas.png\">StringTubeMeas.png</a> </p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/q4pPyA1PYTgCyrj5_CTYDNlS/StringTubeMeas.png\" title=\"StringTubeMeas.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/q4pPyA1PYTgCyrj5_CTYDNlS/StringTubeMeas.png\"></a></div><p>I would like to define a nondeterministic measurement of the string within the tube by sampling from this observation like this:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/FtU7yZacqMpEtvgMiCX_esbx/MonadSample.png\">MonadSample.png</a> </p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/FtU7yZacqMpEtvgMiCX_esbx/MonadSample.png\" title=\"MonadSample.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/FtU7yZacqMpEtvgMiCX_esbx/MonadSample.png\"></a></div><p>Does this seem like a sensible thing to do?</p>",
        "id": 222962297,
        "sender_full_name": "Christoph Thies",
        "timestamp": 1610775877
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The motivation behind Schmid et al's work is to have a formalism for distinguishing inference and causation. Is this sort of thing important for you? Do you need to distinguish between the biological processes and the measurement in the sitring diagrams? Because if you don't, then it's simpler: you just copy on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PZ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> and applying the sampling map to one of the copies (which corresponds to extracting a random member of the population and looking at it).</p>\n<p>What Schmid et al do largely seems to be to take the distinction between inference and causation into account by drawing the inference wires horizontally and the causation wires vertically, so that the whole string diagram is supposed to be read diagonally from the bottom left to the top right.</p>",
        "id": 222963870,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1610778423
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am interested in Schmid et al.'s work because I would like to talk clearly about processes, the formalism that represents them, and the inferential structures used to find them in nature.</p>\n<p>The reason I would like to treat these monad variables explicitly is that I consider populations of populations (metapopulations), that is elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>P</mi><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PPZ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span>. To these, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{samp}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.63888em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">s</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">p</span></span></span></span></span> can be applied once to get an element of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PZ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> (a population) and again to get an element of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> (a sample). A metapopulation in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>P</mi><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PPZ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> therefore yields two random variables, one over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> and one over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PZ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span>. Since the relation between these two is crucial, I would like to represent them.</p>",
        "id": 222965343,
        "sender_full_name": "Christoph Thies",
        "timestamp": 1610779503
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right, I understand that you need the monad around, that makes perfect sense. But I was actually meaning to ask about the measurement: it would be simpler to represent it just as copy on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PZ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span>, composed with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>p</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>P</mi><mi>Z</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">samp : PZ \\to Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> on the right copy. The price for pay for this simpler description is that the string diagram then has no formal distinction between the \"real\" population and the copy population to which the measurement samp is applied. So my question is, do you actually <em>need</em> such a formal distinction? Because if not, then this simpler description is the way to go.</p>",
        "id": 222966946,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1610782264
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see what you mean now. Yes, I think that'd be the same.</p>\n<p>A string diagram as in Schmid et al. represents an experiment. I would like to use the measurement operation in order to explain how measurements at different stages of the experiment are related.</p>",
        "id": 222970397,
        "sender_full_name": "Christoph Thies",
        "timestamp": 1610787674
    }
]